<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / MP urges halt to work on pit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Conservative MP yesterday urged the government to intervene to prevent
British Coal removing more equipment from a pit for which it is considering
rival bids by two companies.
Mr Peter Atkinson, MP for Hexham, is questioning why British Coal has
intensified what he described as 'scorched-earth activities' at Wearmouth
Colliery, Sunderland, while giving assurances that no equipment will leave
Ellington, Northumberland, while a private takeover remains possible.
Mr Atkinson accused British Coal of stripping Wearmouth of all essential
equipment before a decision was made on private bids.
The MP said bidders were concerned at the continuing removal of coal-cutting
equipment and hydraulic roof supports. Such new equipment can cost more than
Pounds 5m per face and may be hard to replace.
Mr Atkinson said British Coal on Friday ordered removal of the shearer and
supports from Wearmouth's second face, a move which would leave the pit with
no cutting equipment. He doubted that Longannet in Scotland, where both
Wearmouth shearers are being sent, needed so much equipment.
His comments coincided with confirmation that new cutting equipment was
delivered to Ellington and sent underground this month, barely 48 hours
before the closure announcement. 'Until a pit's closure is announced things
carry on as normal,' said British Coal yesterday.
Wearmouth bidders had been told what equipment would remain, it said. In
December, the corporation said it planned to remove equipment with a
written-down value of Pounds 8.3m from the pit.
</TEXT>
