<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Prescott in row on private finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour leftwingers yesterday accused Mr John Prescott, shadow employment
secretary, of 'bouncing' the party into accepting plans for sympathetic
treatment of private financing for infrastructure projects.
The row follows the weekend release of a discussion paper on investment
which leftwingers fear may lead to a scaling down of government projects
funded by tax and borrowing. 'This was never discussed,' said one leftwing
member of the shadow cabinet. 'This is a major initiative, and I am very
worried about both the substance and the presentation. We have been
bounced.'
The document was co-authored by Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry
secretary, and Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, for a symposium on
infrastructure investment later this week. Mr Brown told BBC Radio from
Geneva: 'It is the duty of a Labour chancellor to look at how we can use the
resources we have to best effect.'
The document, however, is widely believed to have been prompted by Mr
Prescott, who has been pressing the case for greater use of private funds in
infrastructure projects for several years.
There was some dismay among leftwingers about the involvement of Mr
Prescott, whose roots are on the left of the party. Mr Prescott said the
shadow cabinet and Labour's national executive committee had been kept
informed of discussions on the document 'at every stage'.
Mr Prescott blamed the row on inaccurate briefings to newspapers by unnamed
Labour 'spin doctors' who had not read the document. 'It is not very
helpful, frankly,' he said. 'This is a document about accountancy, not
socialism. There is no reason why there should be a problem.'
The document says there is scope for much greater use of private finance in
the provision of transport infrastructure, inner-city redevelopment,
training, housing, childcare and defence diversification. It also suggests a
limited application in the provision of publicly led projects in education
and health.
The document calls for 'imaginative' financing solutions, such as
transferral of development benefits and regulatory changes in return for
investment. Ideas include:
Clearer rules on risk division, project-approval procedures and intellectual
property rights.
Redefinition of the public sector borrowing requirement to exclude
government-owned trading companies.
Relaxation of Treasury controls on jointly financed projects to take account
of social benefits.
A cut in the required rate of return, now 8 per cent, to between 6.5 per
cent and 7.5 per cent, the average real return on private non-oil assets.
Assessment rules giving priority to job-creating projects.
A task force to resolve problems, and an 'investment broker' to investigate
proposals, leaving the government to decide on priorities.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, said the document
amounted to a disguised attempt to embrace the government's private finance
initiative of 1992.
Joe Rogaly, Page 20
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
