<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / University cuts first-year intake
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The University of East Anglia will cut its intake of first-year students by
8 per cent this year because of cuts in government funding.
The university said the cut was 'much greater than had been expected', and
that there were 65,000 more students in the English university system in
October 1993 than the Treasury had expected to pay for.
Figures on next year's grants for each university will be announced next
week by the Higher Education Funding Council for England. Both the funding
council and the Committee of Vice-chancellors and Principals suggested that
East Anglia's cut might prove exceptional, and predicted an average
reduction closer to 3 per cent.
