<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Sports Council complaints backed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A top Whitehall official acknowledged yesterday that there had been
justifiable complaints about recent financial management and practices at
the Sports Council, the government body charged with promoting sporting
activity in the UK.
Mr Hayden Phillips, permanent secretary at the Department of National
Heritage, told MPs that the Sports Council had not established a proper
'arms-length relationship' with a subsidiary trust company that it had set
up in 1990.
He also accepted a claim from the National Audit Office, the government's
accountancy watchdog, that 'potential conflicts of interest' had been
created by the award of a tender to a company whose chairman and principal
shareholder was the Sports Council's finance director.
Mr Phillips, whose department administers the Sports Council's affairs, was
giving evidence to the Public Accounts Committee, the committee of backbench
MPs which examines how public money is spent.
Yesterday's enquiry was given no evidence of financial impropriety. However,
the complexity of the council's arrangements was frequently criticised by
PAC members. Mr Alan Williams, Labour MP for Swansea, said 'it would be hard
to think of a way of organising financial arrangements more likely to arise
suspicion.'
Mr Phillips said that there was some merit to claims that there had not been
full transparency of cashflows between the council and a trust company which
it had set up in 1990. 'The potential conflicts of interest in the
relationship between the trust company and the council did cause real
concern,' he told MPs. The main decisions had preceded the setting up of the
department in 1992.
'I quite accept that the sort of arrangement whereby the same person appears
in different capacities is one which should be avoided,' he said.
</TEXT>
