<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Tory peers reject clause on police
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday suffered a further embarrassing setback in the
House of Lords at the hands of Conservative backbench critics of the police
and magistrates courts bill.
Peers voted 107 to 100 to reject plans to speed up police disciplinary
procedures after Earl Ferrers, the Home Office minister of state, ignored
Tory calls to back down.
The defeat is the first since the bill entered its committee stage last
week. However, Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, has also backed down twice
to avoid a vote.
Peers from all parties supported the amendment, moved by Lord Bethell, a
Conservative adviser to the Police Federation, who said there was 'deep
concern' among police officers about the bill.
The bill would have removed from the statute book provisions guaranteeing
legal representation to police officers accused of disciplinary offences.
Backbench peers said the proposals would place police officers in danger of
double jeopardy - being tried twice for the same offence.
The government faces further trouble today when the Lords debates provisions
intended to streamline the judicial system by improving the administration
of magistrates courts.
Conservative backbenchers have tabled a series of amendments opposing
government plans to reform the duties of magistrates' clerks and to
introduce fixed-term contracts.
The proposals were strongly opposed by Tory peers during the second-reading
debate. However, in spite of growing backbench unrest, the government has
pressed ahead.
</TEXT>
