<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / World Trade News: McDonnell Douglas in talks on engine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SINGAPORE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
McDonnell Douglas of the US is expected to select the joint aero-engine
venture between the German car maker BMW and the UK aero-engine group
Rolls-Royce to supply the power plant for its new MD-95 100-seater airliner.
Mr Richard Turner, Rolls-Royce's group marketing director, yesterday said at
a Financial Times Asia Aerospace Conference in Singapore that 'detailed
discussions' with the US manufacturer were under way to supply a more
powerful version of the BR-700 engine being developed by BMW Rolls-Royce for
the new MA-95 twin-engine aircraft.
The decision is a setback for Deutsche Aerospace, whose MTU engine
subsidiary in partnership with General Electric and Pratt &amp; Whitney of the
US and Snecma of France, are proposing to develop a rival engine to the
BR-700.
BMW Rolls-Royce is also proposing the BR-700 to re-engine older McDonnell
Douglas DC-9 twin-engine airliners. It has already been chosen by Gulf
Stream of the US to power its GV, the business jet, and by Canadair for its
Global Express long-range corporate jet. But the proposed deals with
McDonnell Douglas would enable the Anglo-German venture to break into the
much bigger regional jet airliner market.
Mr Turner said the first full BR-700 engine would start testing later this
year, although the engine core had already run successfully.
Mr Robert Hood, president of the Douglas Aircraft Company, said the US
company would soon start marketing to potential airline customers the MD-95,
a derivative of the company's 130-seat MD-90 and the larger MD-80. All these
twin-engine airliners are derivatives of the older DC-9s.
Aircraft makers expect the market for 100-seater regional jets to show
strong growth in the next 15 years.
Saudi Arabia's decision to award a Dollars 6bn contract for commercial jets
to Boeing and McDonnell Douglas will cost the European aerospace industry up
to 20,000 jobs, Mr Jean Pierson, managing director of the Airbus consortium,
said in Singapore yesterday.
</TEXT>
