<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Lagos still hopes to reach policy pact with IMF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN, Africa Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nigeria has not abandoned efforts to reach a policy agreement with the
International Monetary Fund, Mr Kalu Kalu, the country's finance minister,
told a press conference in London yesterday.
The minister, who meets British officials today on the first leg of a tour
of the main western capitals to explain the government's policy,
acknowledged there was little prospect of an early agreement with the Fund.
The recent IMF mission to Nigeria had 'no problems on the objectives of the
(1994) budget but they expressed reservations on how the objectives we have
set ourselves would be achieved by controlling the foreign exchange rate and
interest rates,' said Mr Kalu.
But he said it remained an open question whether some of the direct controls
recently imposed would continue in 1995.
Western creditors last night saw this as a hint that the government might be
prepared to reconsider its decision to fix the naira's exchange rate at 22
to the US dollar.
The free market value is half of that.
The minister said he was concerned by rise of arrears in service payments on
the country's Dollars 28bn (Pounds 19bn) external debt. Last year arrears
reached Dollars 6bn and are expected to exceed Dollars 8.5bn by the end of
this year.
This assumes that Nigeria will allocate up to 30 per cent of its export
earnings for debt servicing, and a projected oil price of Dollars 14 a
barrel.
If the price dropped below Dollars 14, said the minister, 'we will have to
put another hole in our belts', adding that debt service payments were
already at the 'barest minimum'.
