<PROFILE>_AN-EBVDKADVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / IG Metall to limit its fire in wage battle: Stoppage next
month will expand across north Germany unless deal reached
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IG Metall, the German engineering workers' union, is set to begin strike
action in the north German state of Lower Saxony on March 7.
Union leaders said yesterday the strike would start there if, as they
expected, this was agreed in a local ballot of workers.
If the walkout fails to force employers to agree to union demands within two
weeks, the strike will be broadened through northern Germany, Mr Klaus
Zwickel, IG Metall chairman, threatened.
Despite the confrontational stance, Germany's biggest union was at pains to
spell out it had no wish to drive companies to the wall in the country's
severe recession.
The choice of Lower Saxony was designed to minimise the impact of the strike
on industry, Mr Zwickel explained. 'We want to avoid massive social
conflict,' he added.
The strike will initially affect only 90,000 workers at 230 companies. If it
spreads to Hamburg, Bremen and Schleswig-Holstein, a further 170,000 workers
at 380 businesses will be involved.
The numbers are small compared to the 1m metalworkers in the state of
Baden-Wurttemberg in the south-west, traditionally an area where strikes
have started in order to have maximum impact.
Moreover, the union stressed it wanted to avoid disruptive knock-on effects
and would steer clear of sectors worst hit by the current downturn.
'In order to keep the conflict within boundaries, we will at first call out
strikes at companies where there will be no knock-on effect in the metal and
electrical industries,' Mr Zwickel said.
Companies in the troubled car components sector, of which there are many in
Lower Saxony, will not be affected by the strike call. Nor will financially
troubled companies in other sectors be targeted, the union said. The strike
will have no impact on Volkswagen, the car group based in Lower Saxony: its
workers are covered by a separate agreement with the union.
The stoppage seems aimed at financially stable companies, primarily in
machine tools.
Union members will be balloted between March 1 and 3. The decision to
postpone further strike action until two weeks after the beginning of a
strike in Lower Saxony shows the union's desire to avoid conflict, Mr
Zwickel argued.
'It is up to the employers to decide whether the strike remains within
boundaries or whether it becomes a full-scale conflict,' he declared.
IG Metall's tactics seem designed to put pressure on the Gesamtmetall
employers' association to reach a compromise in the pay talks, which broke
down after both sides had made significant concessions.
The union has already stepped back from its initial claim for wage rises of
up to 6 per cent, while employers have relented in their calls to abolish
holiday bonuses. The dispute now centres on how employees should be paid for
working flexible hours.
</TEXT>
