<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Firms could be barred under PIA regime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A number of firms in the financial services industry could be prevented from
doing business by the proposed new watchdog body intended to improve
protection for private investors.
The Personal Investment Authority, which yesterday published details of how
it intended to work, gave a clear warning that firms approved by present
regulators would not be guaranteed acceptance under the new regime.
Mr Joe Palmer, the authority's chairman, said: 'Though we'll be relying on
data from existing regulators, the standards and decision-making are the
PIA's'
Ms Colette Bowe, PIA chief executive, emphasised that the onus would be on
firms to show why they should be admitted to the regulator, rather than on
the regulator to admit them.
Up to 6,000 individuals and firms, from small independent financial advisers
to large banks, building societies and life companies, could be eligible to
apply for membership.
The authority expects to be in operation by mid-July this year, but still
faces resistance from some sections of the financial services industry,
including several leading life insurance companies.
The PIA's hand in overcoming industry opposition was strengthened yesterday
by a statement from the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief
regulator, that it was 'minded to recognise' the PIA as the new watchdog for
private investors, and that it intended to end its recognition of present
retail regulators.
This means that members of Lautro, the self-regulatory organisation for the
life insurance industry, and Fimbra, the self-regulatory organisation for
independent financial advisers, with misgivings about the PIA will not be
able to remain under their present regulators indefinitely.
Instead, firms will have to choose between being regulated by the PIA or
directly by the SIB, which has hinted it might 'sub-contract' this task to
the PIA.
There was a cautious reaction from the financial industry to the authority's
prospectus but it was largely welcomed by existing regulators. Lautro
highlighted the improvements in procedures for dealing with complaints
against members and the 'risk-based' approach to regulation.
The Consumers' Association called the PIA the 'last chance for
self-regulation' and urged the new body to 'ratchet up the threshold of
minimum competence'. The PIA has faced some criticism for deciding that
people working in the financial services industry should make up only 10 of
the 21 board members.
Mr Palmer insisted the plans still amounted to self-regulation. Mr Anthony
Nelson, Treasury economic secretary, urged potential PIA members to
'consider the prospectus positively'.
Ground rules spelt out, Page 10
Editorial Comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
