<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Western leaders divided on next move in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM, JUDY DEMPSEY and JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Disagreements between western capitals were emerging yesterday over how to
capitalise on the ceasefire and continuing demilitarisation in the Bosnian
capital, Sarajevo.
President Bill Clinton promised to renew US efforts to achieve peace in
Bosnia, using the 'breathing space' won by Nato's apparent success in
forcing the withdrawal of heavy guns from around Sarajevo.
But he remained wary about issuing further ultimatums in other areas of
Bosnia, cautioning that Nato should 'not undertake a mission it is not able
to perform'.
However, Mr Willy Claes, Belgium's foreign minister, said Nato should be
ready to go further: 'The Nato partners . . . in consultation with the UN,
should tell the parties concerned in Bosnia that we will not hesitate to
widen this measure to other places in Bosnia if there too the hostilities do
not stop.'
Nato and the United Nations called off plans for air strikes after Bosnian
Serbs and government forces moved or handed in their heavy artillery by the
Sunday midnight deadline.
Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, warned that the threat of air
strikes remained. 'If there are heavy weapons discovered within the
exclusion zone or if they go back in there, they are subject to attack by
Nato,' he said before meeting Mr Haris Silajdzic, Bosnia's prime minister.
US officials said they would look at ways of encouraging peace moves at
talks with the UK, France, Germany, Russia and the European Union in Bonn
today. The possibilities included efforts to arrange an agreement between
the Moslem-led Bosnian government and the Bosnian Croats so as to increase
the isolation of the Bosnian Serbs, and a widening of the Nato ultimatum to
ease conditions in other besieged towns such as Tuzla, Srebrenica or Mostar.
Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, said any ultimatum to help other
cities in Bosnia was 'weeks away' and Nato's priority was to make sure
Sarajevo remained free from shelling.
But a UN official in New York said the UN planned to reopen Tuzla airport on
March 7 in an operation that could involve close air support.
Mr Francois Mitterrand, the French president, said yesterday that France
would ask the UN security council this week to put Sarajevo under UN
administration. It was vital, he said, to build quickly on the success of
Nato's ultimatum.
The need to maintain momentum was echoed by Mr Douglas Hurd, Britain's
foreign secretary, who was speaking in Paris after talks with Mr Edouard
Balladur, the French premier.
Sarajevo guns set to find new targets, Page 3
Editorial Comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
