<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Shephard says probe of French
pig aid does not go far enough
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK agriculture minister Mrs Gillian Shephard yesterday welcomed European
Commission moves to investigate alleged illegal state aid to French pig
producers but said they did not go far enough.
Speaking at the farm council in Brussels, Mrs Shephard said: 'Although the
French authorities announced two schemes, for FFr30m (Pounds 3.5m) and
FFr300m in September and October last year, the commission action appears to
be against only the first scheme.'
Britain's National Farmers' Union, complaining to Brussels last week, said
the French payments were causing the UK pig industry to bleed to death.
Urging swift action by the commission, Mrs Shephard said pig producers
throughout the European Union had suffered for the past year from
oversupply, because of an expansion in pig herds in most member states.
'France is as much to blame as anyone,' she said. 'By introducing its own
national measures, the French government adds to the problems in every other
country, and rewards its own producers who have contributed to the
oversupply and current market difficulties.'
Special aid is not the only form of financial support for continental pig
producers that encourages expansion and puts British producers at a
disadvantage, according to a report by the UK Meat and Livestock Commission.
Corporate tax arrangements are more flexible in Denmark, France and the
Netherlands than in Britain, it says. 'The main areas of flexibility that
could be encouraged in Britain are in the depreciation of capital
investment, the ability to average net income over a three- to five-year
period and the use of tax credits for training.'
Institutions lending to pig farmers see them as a lower risk on the
continent than is the case in Britain, and price stabilisation schemes also
help, the report says.
It adds that 'a striking feature of the Danish, French and Dutch pig
production systems is the degree of producer co-operation, normally
encouraged by respective governments.'
This provides strong links between producers, processors and retailers,
improved power when buying supplies, and an ability to negotiate
advantageous loans. 'Whereas almost 100 per cent of pig production in
Denmark, France and Netherlands is covered by collaborative arrangements,
the coverage for Britain is only about 40 per cent.'
The report says a British ban on the use of sow tethers and stalls in 1999
will bring extra costs for producers compared with their European
counterparts. 'This change is a watershed and may result in major
disinvestment by a significant proportion of the industry,' it concludes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P0213 Hogs.
    P9641 Regulation of Agricultural Marketing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Production.
</TP>
