FT  22 FEB 94 / International Company News: Bikuben returns to the black but
cuts payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bikuben, the savings bank, has cut its annual dividend to DKr5 from DKr6 a
share despite moving back into profit after two years of losses.
The group made a pre-tax profit of DKr193m (Dollars 28.7m) last year
compared with a 1992 loss of DKr1.17bn. Financial income increased to
DKr5.54bn from DKr3.67bn and costs were down to DKr2.78bn from DKr2.87bn.
But after bad debt provisions, which rose to DKr2.69bn from DKr1.75bn, there
was an operating loss of DKr132m against a 1992 loss of DKr1.09bn. Only
extraordinary income of DK325m enabled the savings bank to report a small
profit.
Mr Borge Munk Ebbesen, chief executive, described the result as 'not
satisfactory'. Total assets increased to DKr100m from DKr95m and the group
said the capital adequacy ratio was 11.1 per cent compared with the Danish
minimum level of 9 per cent.
