FT  22 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Smirnoff aims at Kazak market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Grand Metropolitan has formed a joint venture to market Smirnoff vodka in
the former Soviet republic of Kazakhstan.
Having seen dramatic growth in Smirnoff sales in Russia, GrandMet's IDV
spirits arm is now keen to attack the Kazak vodka market which is 40 per
cent bigger than the UK.
Mr Paul Curtis, IDV's head of international marketing, said:'Kazakhstan
represents another great opportunity for developing the strength of IDV's
international brands in emerging markets.
'We are uniquely positioned with Smirnoff, which is already available and
well known in some of the major cities.'
He said there was also potential for IDV's other brands which include J&amp;B
Rare Scotch whisky.
IDV, which recently secured US distribution rights to Stolichnaya Russian
vodka, has been marketing US-made Smirnoff in Russia since 1989. Last year
it sold 600,000 cases in Russia, compared with just 10,000 cases in 1991. In
June, the Pierre Smirnoff Company set up its own office in Moscow.
The new Kazakhstan company, called IDV Central Asia, is a joint venture with
Coromin Inc, an importer and marketing company with warehousing and
transport facilities.
Unilever has acquired 90 per cent of the shares in Severnoye Siyaniye, a St
Petersburg-based producer of lotions, after-shaves and colour cosmetics.
