<DATE>940222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Rover and Honda - Going Their Own Ways: Capable of producing
from the ground up - The loss of its Japanese partner does not necessarily
present a significant setback for the UK carmaker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A critical question faces Rover Group. How will it survive without Honda's
technology and expertise in the wake of their failed relationship?
Rover has 2,000 design, development and engineering staff. It has the
capability to take a car from first concept on a computer screen to
production, with no outside help. This capability includes the design,
development and production of engines and gearboxes.
Senior Rover executives insist that this capability has not been utilised to
the full during the period of Rover's 15-year partnership with Honda, for
straightforward commercial reasons rather than for any lack of technical
ability.
There is no logic, they maintain, in Rover developing wholly separate
vehicles or powertrains for market slots that can be occupied perfectly
adequately by shared development models enjoying good economies of scale.
And Rover's full technical capability will in any case be amply demonstrated
in new, as-yet secret, models already scheduled for production and in which
Honda has played no part, according to Mr John Towers, Rover's chief
executive.
That such core expertise has been retained by Rover is easily overlooked,
however, given that the UK car maker being sold to BMW appears to have been
so overwhelmingly dependent on Honda.
Two of Rover's key model ranges, the 600 and 200/400 saloons, are the
subject of simple licensing agreements with Honda or are joint developments,
while a key Rover gearbox is also a Honda design made under licence. All the
licence agreements can be terminated by Honda at three months' notice.
Mr Bernd Pischetsrieder, BMW's chairman, has indicated that BMW will be more
than willing to place some of BMW's own 6,000 engineers at Rover's disposal
as future new model plans develop without Honda.
'6,000 BMW engineers? - I don't know what we'd do with them,' said one Rover
executive yesterday. 'We are fully capable of seeing through our new car
projects.'
Where Rover executives and engineers, many of whom regret the loss of Honda
as a long-term partner, do see major benefits in BMW's ownership is in the
finan-cial resources that they expect to be made avail-able.
Currently Rover spends some Pounds 200m a year on new model development,
bringing cars into production and upgrading or maintaining plant and
equipment to build them.
This is a very small amount by mainstream motor industry standards, and Mr
Pischetsrieder has indicated that he would expect to see Rover increase it
to at least 7 per cent of its Pounds 4.3bn of annual sales, or slightly more
than Pounds 300m a year.
That would give Rover the ability to bring to fruition various new model
ideas which have been beyond its financial grasp.
'All car makers have more model ideas than finance, and so have to
prioritise what is actually built,' the company said yesterday.
Rover's design, research, development, and engineering facilities are more
extensive than many realise.
They are concentrated at Canley, near Birmingham, and at a vast, 900-acre
complex including 26 miles of test track at Gaydon in Warwickshire.
The Gaydon facility, currently employing 900 engineers and the subject of a
Pounds 100m-plus new building programme, includes: climatic wind tunnels,
prototype build centre, structural analysis facilities, electro-magnetic
compatibility centre to test car computer and wiring systems, component test
laboratories, noise, vibration and harshness analysis centre, engine test
beds and anechoic (sound-free) chambers.
It contains within it the capability to develop engines from scratch. It is
where Rover's state-of-the-art K series multi-valve engine was developed and
which in turn is being developed from a small-capacity four cylinder unit
into a full range of engines, including a V6, capable of powering almost any
vehicle Rover might make in the future.
Commercial logic once again dictates, however, that BMW and other
manufacturers' units are used instead in some applications, such as diesels,
where they can be simply taken 'off the shelf'. Peugeot diesels, for
example, are used in Rover 200, 400 and Metro ranges.
The Canley centre is occupied by some 1,000 designers and engineers, where
vehicles are styled from scratch, and where a master database of dimensions
and other elements is created off which Rover's and component suppliers'
project engineers can work.
However, one of the most valuable benefits Rover has gained from its long
relationship with Honda has been how to break down old barriers between the
various development departments and use simultaneous engineering to bring
products to market more quickly and with many fewer mistakes in the build-up
to production.
Honda has changed Rover's methodology radically, to the extent that new
vehicle projects are not even centred at Gardon or Canley, but at the plant
where they are to be built.
For the 600, for example, a project leader was appointed at the Cowley
manufacturing plant. He appointed a team and they 'lived' within just one
room while ideas for the car took shape. Gaydon and Canley personnel simply
became part of the project team.
It is this Honda-taught approach to development, costs and quality which
allowed Rover to take its Discovery four-wheel-drive model into production
in a record-breaking 21 months and is where, Rover executives acknowledge,
Rover's greatest debt to Honda lies.
Understandably perhaps, Honda is not anxious to see it all handed to such a
fierce rival on a plate.
