<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Small price to pay for prime seat: George Soros and John
Ritblat have moved to gain control of the Broadgate centre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The announcement that Mr John Ritblat's British Land has bought a stake in
Stanhope, a struggling developer, has turned the spotlight on Broadgate, the
City of London complex which is Stanhope's main asset.
For a small outlay, Mr Ritblat has won a seat at the negotiating table, from
which he intends to gain control of Stanhope's Broadgate assets.
The deal was greeted by analysts as a potentially important deal for British
Land. 'It looks as though John Ritblat is making sure that he either gets
Broadgate through the corporate route, or that he has a ringside seat
whenever it goes up for sale,' said Mr Chris Turner, director of research at
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Securities.
'This is potentially another big hit by British Land,' says Mr Robert Fowlds
of Kleinwort Benson.
'Mr Ritblat is paying a small amount for potentially a slice of a Pounds 1bn
property.'
It is not yet clear whether Stanhope will play according to Mr Ritblat's
plans, although its alternatives appear limited.
Stanhope also appeared to query the validity of the stake acquisition by
drawing attention to the pre-emption rights belonging to Mr Stuart Lipton,
Stanhope's chief executive, by which he would have first refusal on the
shares that originally belonged to Olympia &amp; York.
If British Land succeeds in achieving its goal, the prize could be a
substantial one.
Stanhope owns a half share of Broadgate Properties, which owns six buildings
in the Broadgate Development, as well as the 600,000 sq ft Ludgate
Development on the western edge of the City of London.
It also has pre-emption rights over the other half, which is controlled by
the receivers of Rosehaugh.
Broadgate was one of the largest developments to be built in the 1980s.
At a ceremony during the building work in July 1986, Lady Thatcher, the
former prime minister, described it as the largest development in the City
since the Great Fire of London in 1666.
The Pounds 2bn development was successful in attracting the financial
services industry as it expanded in the aftermath of 1986's Big Bang. Its
large buildings, constructed to accommodate the computer cabling and
air-conditioning needed by large trading floors, succeeded in persuading a
workforce of some 20,000 to move to hitherto unfamiliar territory north-east
of the City.
Broadgate and Ludgate have been affected by falls in the London office
market, where values have fallen by two-thirds from the peak of the market
three years ago. Half of Broadgate has been sold, and the two are now worth
about Pounds 1bn.
Broadgate was a remarkably ambitious scheme for two small companies. Carried
out in partnership with the British Rail Property Board, it was conceived in
1983 by Mr Lipton and Mr Godfrey Bradman, both property entrepreneurs.
The key for such relatively insubstantial companies to build such a large
development lay in the use of non-recourse loans - commonplace in the US but
new to the UK. These allowed the borrower to confine the security of the
loan to specific assets, rather than the parent company.
Despite Broadgate's success in attracting prestigious tenants, it was not
enough to cushion its developers from the downturn which hit the industry in
1990. Rosehaugh was one of the first large property companies to signal the
coming problems, when it announced a Pounds 125m rights issue in 1990. Its
losses continued to mount and in December 1992 the company was put into
receivership.
Stanhope has struggled on, courtesy of its bankers. Its net assets fell from
Pounds 458m in 1990 to a minus Pounds 15.8m in June 1993. Asset values have
started to appreciate again, but the company has continued to suffer
operating losses and its existence remains contingent on the approval of its
bankers. Several months ago, it began work on a Pounds 160m restructuring
plan, which involved raising new funds and merging with its associate
Broadgate Properties. Analysts expected to see some results last month, but
progress so far has been limited.
British Land said yesterday that it intended to play a role in Stanhope's
restructuring plans. Mr Ritblat said, however, that he was not interested in
gaining control of Stanhope, or even in having board representation. 'Our
objective is to ensure that Stanhope remains independent,' he said. 'We
would not expect to play an active role in the company.'
In his view, the solution to Stanhope's problems is to sell Broadgate and
Ludgate - and in the process offload the large debt they carry.
'We want to stabilise Stanhope and provide some some seed capital. We know
what we want to do,' he said.
</TEXT>
