<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / OFT to investigate safeguards in pre-payment of funerals
schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading launched an investigation yesterday into
Britain's growing pre-paid funeral business.
The inquiry follows the collapse last month of a Yorkshire-based company
running a pre-payment scheme and comes amid concern about the lack of
regulation of a business that could attract billions of pounds.
In the US, one funeral in seven is pre-paid, and pre-payment schemes have
won up to 40 per cent of the market in some states.
Pre-paid schemes currently account for 3 per cent of the Pounds 70m-a-year
funeral business in the UK. The OFT estimates 100,000 plans have been sold
and expects the market to expand to 150,000 a year.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said the financial
implications of the growth of pre-paid funerals were considerable. If 25 per
cent of the UK's 20 million people over the age of 50 eventually bought
plans worth about Pounds 1,000 each, the funeral companies' funds would be
holding Pounds 5bn.
These funds would not be regulated or safeguarded, he said. Proper
arrangements were needed to cover the appointment and powers of trustees and
the deployment of returns from investing pre-payments. The funds should be
kept separately from shareholders' funds.
It was also important to ensure that elderly and vulnerable people were not
sold over-elaborate schemes they could not afford, and that plans purchased
decades before a person's death were honoured or a refund paid to the
person's estate, Sir Bryan said.
The four main companies providing pre-paid funeral schemes - market leader
Chosen Heritage, Dignity, Golden Charter and CWS, the Co-operative Wholesale
Society - offer a variety of plans ranging in cost from about Pounds 750 to
more than Pounds 5,000. The average cost is Pounds 850 to Pounds 1,200.
The companies believe they already provide many of the safeguards the OFT is
looking for through two voluntary regulatory bodies.
Dignity and Chosen Heritage are members of the National Association of
Pre-Paid Funeral Plans, and Golden Charter and CWS co-founded the Funeral
Planning Council.
Both bodies are working on codes of practice covering pre-paid schemes and
demand that member companies hold pre-paid funeral fees in independent trust
funds with separate custodian trustees.
More use pre-paid burial or cremation plans, Page 9
Rule change may push up funeral costs, Page 9
</TEXT>
