FT  22 FEB 94 / Embargo against Macedonia illegal, Brussels tells Greece
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission yesterday branded as illegal Greece's partial trade
embargo against Macedonia and warned that the Athens government risked being
taken to the European Court of Justice.
The warning came as Greece, which holds the rotating EU presidency, found
itself isolated at a European foreign ministers' meeting in Brussels.
Ministers deplored Greece's unilateral action against the former Yugoslav
republic and demanded an explanation.
Mr Theodoros Pangalos, Greek minister for European affairs, pledged to
submit to Brussels a legal defence of the embargo shortly, and hinted that
it would be based on public security grounds. Mr Hans Van den Broek,
commissioner for external political affairs, is to visit Athens and the
Macedonian capital Skopkje, probably tomorrow and on Thursday.
He will attempt to mediate in the crisis caused by a dispute over
Macedonia's name and use of an ancient Greek symbol, the Vergina, on its
flag.
However, a Brussels official made clear that the commissioner would not
negotiate on the embargo. This was being tackled separately by the
Commission.
Greece last week banned the movement of oil and other goods through the
Greek port of Thessaloniki without informing or consulting its EU partners.
The partial embargo followed the US decision to extend diplomatic
recognition to Macedonia. This move seems to have prompted the Greek
Socialist government to harden its position - even at the expense of
alienating the European Commission and Greece's EU partners.
In Brussels yesterday, the Commission described the trade embargo as an
infraction of the Treaty of Rome providing for the free circulation of goods
inside the European Union.
At the foreign ministers' meeting, there were also signs that Athens' action
has weakened already fragile confidence in the impartiality of the Greek
presidency.
