<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: Unravelling bonds
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There is something perverse about the weakness of European bond markets.
Inflation is well under control in the main European economies. The
continental recovery has barely started, while in the UK a sizeable output
gap remains. The weak oil price hardly indicates general concern about
inflation. The nervousness obviously reflects worry about the New York bond
market, but that is only part of the story.
There has also been a shift in sentiment among the large US hedge funds,
which until recently have given bond markets an upward momentum of their
own. Their leverage means they cannot afford much capital loss. It was time
for them to start worrying when yields stopped falling at the turn of the
year. The risks became all the greater after the Federal Reserve began to
tighten. Since then, a vicious circle appears to have developed: the more
bond prices fall, the more they are forced to sell.
Such fickle investors may have deluded governments about the ease with which
their deficits could be funded. Now comes the question of who will step into
the breach. Domestic European investors show no real signs of selling, but
they are reluctant to buy bonds yet because, probably rightly, they believe
prices could fall further before the hedge fund sales are absorbed. Once the
immediate storm is passed, judiciously timed cuts in short-term interest
rates would help continental markets. That would encourage investors to
shift out of time deposits, replacing some of the US liquidity which has
evaporated. It would be a pity if the Bundesbank were constrained by a false
concern that the bond market has been sending a message about inflation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
