<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Observer: Making up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Just how far will US President Bill Clinton go to mend fences when he meets
Britain's prime minister next week? After the rows over Ireland and Bosnia,
there is plenty of groundwork in need of urgent repair.
An invitation to sleep for one night in the White House sounds jolly
generous, especially since the last British prime minister to do it was Sir
Winston Churchill. But the US administration's eagerness to rebuild the
special relationship has its limits - notably supporting the UK's nominee
for the head of the Paris-based Organisation for Economic Co-operation and
Development.
Major put Lord Lawson up for the job, but word is that Washington, which
picks up much of the tab for the Pounds 125,000-a-year post, is preparing to
veto that idea.
The Americans believe that the OECD, after a decade in the hands of the
monetarists, would benefit from a secretary-general who made economic
growth, not obsessive control of inflation, his priority. Clearly no one
told them about the Lawson boom.
