<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Observer: Hot wires in Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese don't normally scribble on other people's walls, especially in
Tokyo. So when the local headquarters of the US electronic giant Motorola is
sprayed with an anti-US slogan, people stop and stare.
Not that yesterday's anti-Motorola graffito, sparked by a US threat to
impose sanctions on Japan unless Motorola is treated better, is in
particularly bad taste. In typical Japanese style, it amounts to no more
than a polite cough by US or even European standards. 'Crush the
hard-selling diplomacy of US imperialists . . . ', it reads. Tokyo has not
yet resorted to the tactics of America's Japan-bashers in earlier trade
disputes. Sledgehammers have not been taken to Motorola's mobile phones.
Still, tempers are clearly beginning to hot up in the nine-year-old trade
dispute, despite Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's contention that Japan
and the US have just embarked on a truly adult relationship.
</TEXT>
