<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Leading Article: Dinosaurs eye the PIA
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The stakes in the tortuous game of bluff and double bluff that the
Securities and Investments Board (SIB) has been obliged to play with the
more recalcitrant members of the life assurance industry were raised a
further notch yesterday. In responding to a formal application from the
Personal Investment Authority (PIA) to become the new unitary
self-regulatory organisation for the retail investment business, SIB
simultaneously announced that it was 'minded to recognise' the PIA and
'minded to revoke' recognition of two existing retail investment watchdogs,
Fimbra and Lautro.
Behind the legal jargon lies a difficult set of calculations both for the
regulators and the life assurers. The PIA has to achieve widespread support
before Mr Andrew Large, head of SIB, can obtain the Treasury's permission to
recognise the new unitary watchdog and bring down the curtain on its two
predecessors. Yesterday's publication of a prospectus inviting applications
to join the PIA constituted a formal start to this process.
The task is a formidable one, and not just because a handful of big insurers
are hostile. If the PIA's claim to raise standards in retail financial
services is to carry conviction the new body will have to reject
applications from people who are currently authorised to conduct investment
business. That is not a recipe for popularity in the industry. Nor should it
be.
Meantime the recalcitrants, who rank the Prudential and Standard Life among
their number, have to ask what they can achieve by continuing to oppose the
changes to the existing regime. They would also be well advised to ensure
that a dignified means of retreat is available if their arguments fail to
carry the day. Or, indeed, if they succeed. Treasury ministers may not
relish being railroaded into unwelcome policy options, any more than big
insurance companies enjoy changing their ways to suit the regulators.
Repeated scandals
Part of the problem is that many opponents of the proposed new structure
start from the assumption that they were promised self-regulation under the
original 1986 Financial Services Act regime and are still entitled to it.
This is hopelessly unrealistic in the light of repeated scandals to do with
the industry's sales practices. Public confidence has been severely dented
and will not be restored without some clear indication that the system is
being significantly strengthened. Against that background the special
pleading from leading practitioners about a surfeit of public interest
representatives on the PIA's board is a public relations disaster which
undermines the credibility of the whole industry.
Genuine alternative
Nor does it help to suggest that statutory regulation provides a genuine
alternative to the problem. In the long run it may or may not do: but there
is a crisis in the here and now, and one which urgently needs to be
addressed. To suggest that consumers of financial services should be allowed
to wait for several years while a statutory alternative is put in place
looks, at best, disingenuous. At worst it risks being interpreted as an
attempt by the life assurers to make hay for as long as possible before the
whistle is blown.
A unitary retail watchdog makes sense in a financial world where the
organisational boundaries between banks, insurers and other managers of
personal savings have become anachronistic. There are undoubtedly
shortcomings in the present process of accountability to parliament. It
remains to be seen how effective a watchdog the PIA might become. And there
will no doubt be arguments about specific elements of the PIA's prospectus
and its accompanying document on the new body's approach to regulation.
But only an industry suffering from extreme myopia would fail to recognise
that SIB's current approach is the only half-decent damage limitation
exercise on offer. The hostile insurers do no service to their shareholders,
policyholders or the general public by failing to offer their support. They
should wake up and shut up. The PIA is better than an interminable wait for
an ideal system that may or may not materialise in the year 2000.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
