<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / Rise in legal claims hits top accountancy firms: Auditors
say they are turning away high-risk clients
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's six largest accountancy firms faced about 600 legal claims last
year and paid up to 8 per cent of their audit income on costs related to
legal actions.
The number of claims has risen sharply in recent years, following growing
litigation against auditors in the US, much of it considered by the
profession to be unjustified.
The figures were compiled for two studies as part of a campaign to reform
the law of unlimited liability on auditors and will be submitted to the
Department of Trade and Industry.
The growing size and number of claims makes commercial insurance cover much
more difficult to obtain. Accountancy firms say they have started to turn
away high-risk clients, and begun negotiating limits on their legal
liability for non-audit work.
A working group of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and
Wales tackling litigation claims says the average claims in the largest
three lawsuits last year were nearly Pounds 500m, compared with Pounds 40m
10 years ago. The figures exclude exceptional claims for more than Dollars
8bn relating to the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
The largest claims are several times the average limits on commercial
insurance cover, currently about Dollars 100m (Pounds 68m). Payments higher
than those limits are covered from insurance mutuals and the firms' own
resources.
The working group's paper is to be discussed by the institute's council on
March 2 as part of an effort to win support across the profession for a
campaign by the eight largest accountancy firms.
Separate information compiled by the firms' insurers showing the proportion
of audit income spent on litigation-related costs has been produced at the
request of government officials.
The accountancy firms want section 310 of the 1985 Companies Act removed.
This forbids auditors to negotiate for a cap on their liabilities in the
event that they are sued.
Some observers have criticised the campaign for its self-interest, and
accused the profession of selecting favourable or incomplete data. For
example, the fee income figures to which litigation costs are compared do
not take into account revenues from non-audit income, such as consultancy
work which may have been generated by the audit.
The information on which the calculations are based is also not publicly
available. The firms refuse to publish any of their own financial
information.
</TEXT>
