<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / Boardrooms pressed on standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government-sponsored guide-lines are published today which aim to increase
the professionalism of company directors.
The guidelines were commissioned by the Department of Employment last year
in response to corporate scandals and to concerns that many company boards
do not function properly.
They say chief executives need up to 25 personal attributes including
energy, imagination and openness if they are to be effective.
'I'd be surprised if too many companies were living up to these standards at
the moment,' said Mr Victor Dulewicz of the Henley Management College. 'Most
would admit there is scope for improvement.'
The draft standards, drawn up by the college and the Institute of Directors,
cover every aspect of the skills, composition and behaviour of boards of
directors.
The guidelines say directors have four primary tasks: to establish a
company's vision, mission and values; to set strategy and structure; to
supervise management; and to be responsible to stakeholders.
The standards also establish principles for chairmen to ensure that the
structure of the board is correct and is run in an efficient manner.
The guidelines are likely to meet opposition from many companies which feel
that the behaviour of boards is something that should vary from one company
to another and does not lend itself to fixed rules.
Mr John Harper, development director at the institute and co-author of the
report, said that although the standards did not hold out a promise to make
every company outstandingly successful, they offered a generally applicable
checklist against which companies could measure their performance.
Mr Harper said the lists of requirements for directors were based on the
views of hundreds of board directors interviewed over the past year. He said
that if one board member lacked certain attributes, other board members
should be found who possessed them.
The guidelines are being circulated for discussion and a final version will
be drawn up in the autumn.
The standards, which will be non-binding, are being seen as complementary to
the Cadbury report on the financial aspects of corporate governance which
has laid down guidelines on the accountability of directors of quoted
companies.
</TEXT>
