<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / CBI attacks Clarke over complexity of finance bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is to be warned today that the regulatory
complexity of this year's finance bill will hit 'the innocent as well as the
guilty' and impose 'additional costs' on businesses.
Mr Howard Davies, the Confederation of British Industry's director-general,
has written to Mr Clarke calling for a review of the way new taxes are
drafted and enacted. He is joined by the British Chambers of Commerce.
Mr Davies says 'the massive length and the drafting complexity' of this
year's bill highlights the inadequacies of existing procedures.
'We are not complaining about the government's need to close tax loopholes
which permit abuses of the system,' Mr Davies says. 'But the regulatory
burden imposed by a bill of this magnitude hits the innocent as well as the
guilty and its complexity imposes additional costs on hard-pressed firms
whose managers' time would be better spent on more productive work.'
The Treasury rejected the CBI's criticisms. 'The bill introduced legislation
which was believed to be necessary to help business and bring about a
sustainable recovery,' it said.
Mr Richard Brown, deputy director-general of the British Chambers of
Commerce, said: 'We understand the need for a unified Budget but things have
got out of hand when no businessman has a chance of understanding the tax
system. Ironically, we have a 244-clause finance bill published within days
of the de-regulation bill.'
</TEXT>
