<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / EU environment laws will 'cost companies billions'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The costs to British companies of complying with European Union
environmental policy are continuing to rise and will run into billions of
pounds, says a report published today.
Mr Adrian Wilkes, author of the report by Environmental Policy Consultants,
a London-based consultancy, says: 'A torrent of policy proposals is about to
be unleashed, presenting British business with an unprecedented challenge.'
The survey, which identifies 96 environmental policy proposals in the
pipeline, says all companies will be affected by tighter controls on
pollution, the need to use energy more efficiently and requirements to
disclose information.
The report argues that phasing out HCFCs - chemicals that deplete the
atmosphere's ozone layer - could cost the UK food industry Pounds 500m.
'Britain's political campaign to stop the momentum of Brussels policy-making
has failed,' says Mr Wilkes. Ten days ago Mr Ioannis Paleokrassas, the
environmental commissioner, repeated his refusal to give the UK more time to
comply with water directives.
Environmentalists yesterday attacked the report's conclusions. Mr Andrew
Lees, campaigns director of Friends of the Earth, the pressure group, said:
'It is the member countries and the European Council of Ministers who are
driving this regulation along - it is wrong to blame the (European)
Commission.'
EC Environmental Policy Monitor. Environmental Policy Consultants, 071-372
7122. Pounds 125.
