<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / Barclays says recovery can withstand tax rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The recovery is strong enough to withstand April's tax rises, says Barclays
Bank, in spite of last week's poor economic statistics.
In an upbeat economic review published today, Barclays says interest rates
are close to their low point and are unlikely to go below 5 per cent.
Mr Alan Davies, Barclays' chief economist, says: 'There has been little
general appreciation of just how far the economy has moved away from the
recession.'
He says recent data 'should not detract from the fact that the overall
recovery has been stronger than expected a year ago. Despite some
disappointment with last week's statistics, the balance of evidence still
suggests strengthening demand and output.'
Barclays predicts growth in UK gross domestic product of 2.7 per cent this
year, rising to 2.9 per cent in 1995. Inflation is forecast to reach 3.2 per
cent by the end of this year and 4.2 per cent by the end of 1995.
Unemployment is expected to fall to 2.55m by the end of this year.
Mr Davies says resilient consumer spending and an improvement in the
corporate sector's financial position point to a strengthening recovery.
Also, 'UK exporters are well placed to build on the resilient performance of
the past year'.
Barclays' view of the prospects for the developed economies is the most
optimistic for three years. Mr Davies says: 'Growth will be somewhat
stronger in 1994, with the continuing upturn in the United States being
joined by recoveries in Japan and Europe in response to lower interest
rates.'
Barclays Economic Review. Economics Department, Barclays House, 1 Wimborne
Road, Poole, Dorset BH15 2BB.
