<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / Labour to urge broader role for private finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party will today argue that private finance should be extended
beyond transport and infrastructure in a consultative paper on
public-private partnerships.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor and one of the authors of the new plan,
said the party had 'stolen a march on the Tories' by calling for an
extension of private finance to hospitals, education and inner-city
projects.
The plan is set out in a Labour document called Financing Infrastructure
Investment - Promoting a Partnership between Public and Private Finance.
Labour has long called for private investment for transport infrastructure
projects.
Its latest policy for a public-private partnership is intended to replace
its traditional stance of support for the remaining state-owned
corporations.
Labour's paper says: 'Britain badly needs capital investment across the
whole range of our infrastructure, from the railways to childcare
facilities.
'One potent way of providing it is through promoting a partnership between
public and private finance.'
Mr Brown believes it has proved difficult in practice to bring the elements
together. He will argue today that the government must lead in promoting
partnership between public and private sectors.
The document says: 'We are consulting on a way of setting appropriate profit
performance measures for such bodies.'
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary and another of the
document's authors, said: 'What the paper does is take Treasury rules by the
scruff of the neck and give them a very firm shake in order to open up the
possibility of much greater investment in public enterprise and public
services.'
The document was criticised by Mr Alan Beith, Liberal Democrats' Treasury
spokesman, who accused Labour of joining the Tories in hoping that private
finance would rescue them from tough decisions on tax and spending.
Everyone, including the Liberal Democrats, wanted more private capital to go
into public transport, schools and hospitals, Mr Beith said.
'But at the end of the day you cannot duck the need for significant public
finance, because many of the vital projects cannot produce a commercial
return, and others require a Treasury guarantee because the private sector
simply does not want the level of risk involved.'
</TEXT>
