<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / Dutch propose first tax on mobile phones
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Netherlands is set to become the first country in the world to levy a
special tax on mobile telephones.
The Dutch government is proposing to impose a 7.5 per cent tax on the
profits of companies operating new digital cellular networks, when licences
are issued this year.
The tax has been approved by the Dutch cabinet over objections from the
business community, but it has still to be endorsed by parliament. If it
passes, the two operators of networks built to the pan-European digital GSM
standard will be obliged to pay the tax.
The GSM tax may be taken as a precedent for similar levies elsewhere. The
practice of auctioning cellular mobile licences is well established but, as
mobile telephony moves into the mass consumer market, the medium-term
revenue potential of a special tax is considerable.
The Dutch government argues that the tax will be fair because it plans to
allow only two GSM operators. These are KPN, the state post and
telecommunications company which is slated for privatisation in June, and a
second, private-sector operator which will be chosen in the second half of
1994. The government considered, but rejected, a proposal to charge each
operator an up-front fee of about Fl 500m (Pounds 172m).
Greece, with GDP barely a quarter that of the Netherlands, two years ago
raised the equivalent of Pounds 110m each for two GSM licences. The US
expects to raise more than Dollars 10bn next year in an auction of licences
for Personal Communications Services, a new cellular technology.
The Dutch levy would be on pre-tax profits. Payments would be
tax-deductible, taking the effective rate down to about 5 per cent. There
would be no immediate revenue because it would take operators a few years to
achieve profitability.
The proposed tax, devised by the Dutch Finance Ministry, has been attacked
by KPN and business groups as a 'penalty on innovation' when the Netherlands
is already behind other western European countries in the introduction of
GSM networks. It has also been criticised by the Labour party, the junior
partner in the governing coalition, and by the right-wing Liberals.
However, the prospect of the tax does not appear to have deterred potential
bidders. KPN expects to launch its network in July and competition for the
second licence will be fierce. The three main Dutch banks - ABN Amro, ING
and Rabobank - are expected to put in bids with local and international
telecoms partners.
The second operator is unlikely to get its own GSM network off the ground
before 1995, but KPN will be required to open its network to its competitor
while this second network is being built.
Pakistani phone boom, page 5
</TEXT>
