<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / Nato lifts threat of early air strikes: UN finds substantial
withdrawal of Serb guns - West warns ultimatum remains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY, ROBERT GRAHAM and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, AVIANO, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Tension over Bosnia eased early today as the United Nations said Nato air
strikes against the Bosnian Serbs around Sarajevo were unnecessary 'at this
stage'.
But western officials warned that the threat of air strikes remained unless
the Serbs continued to observe the Nato ultimatum issued earlier this month.
Soon after the deadline for ending the Serb artillery siege of the Bosnian
capital expired at midnight, the UN said there had been substantial
withdrawal or regrouping of the Serb heavy weapons.
Mr Yasushi Akashi, the UN special envoy in former Yugoslavia, said: 'On the
basis of the information available to me, and pending further verification,
I have decided that it is not necessary at this stage for me to request Nato
to use air power.'
In Washington, the White House said all Bosnian Serb heavy guns around
Sarajevo had been neutralised 'or soon should be'. As a result, UN and Nato
commanders had concluded no air strikes were necessary 'at this time', a
senior official said.
Mr Manfred Worner, Nato secretary-general, said there had been effective
compliance with the Nato demand to remove heavy weapons more than 20km from
Sarajevo or put them under UN control under pain of air strikes. 'Nato's
resolve to end the shelling of Sarajevo does not end today,' he added. 'We
shall continue to verify compliance. . . We will remain vigilant.'
The military threat receded after the Nato alliance had assembled in Italy
and the Adriatic Sea the largest forces of air power since the Gulf war.
The Moslem-led Bosnian government yesterday urged Nato to go ahead with air
strikes against the Bosnian Serbs. It accused the UN of conniving with the
Serbs to avert air strikes.
In a bid to reassure the Moslems, General Sir Michael Rose, the UN commander
in Bosnia, warned that if there were any breaches of the Nato ultimatum, 'I
will have no hesitation in calling air strikes'.
In relaxed remarks before the deadline, Gen Rose appeared concerned to
defuse tension. Asked where he would be at the midnight deadline, he told
reporters: 'In bed.'
Pentagon officials said that poor weather made it difficult to determine
immediately how many guns might still be within 20km of Sarajevo. Air
strikes were unlikely to be ordered before a complete assessment could be
made in the daylight today, they added.
But US officials warned that the Nato ultimatum was open-ended, and that air
strikes could be launched at any time if the Serbs did not continue to
comply. They also said western allies would this week discuss expanding the
Sarajevo ultimatum to ease the plight of other besieged Bosnian cities.
Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, said the 'next step is to
consider whether other places in Bosnia should have a comparable treatment',
including the towns of Srbrenica and Gorazde.
Shortly before the midnight deadline, 400 Russian UN peacekeeping troops
moved into Sarajevo to act as a buffer between Moslem-led forces in the
capital and the Serbs who have been besieging the city for 22 months. The
soldiers, in a convoy of 70 armoured vehicles, trucks and jeeps, were moved
from Croatia and will be followed by another 400 men from Russia.
Mr Worner thanked Russia for its role in Bosnia in the past few days, when
it lent its weight to secure Bosnian Serb agreement to withdraw heavy
weapons. 'The just and lasting peace that we must now try to achieve in
Bosnia involves close Russian involvement,' he added. 'We all must try to
maintain the momentum and reflect on further steps.'
President Bill Clinton phoned Russian president Boris Yeltsin yesterday and
told him he was encouraged by Serb efforts to comply with the Nato
ultimatum, a US official said.
Mr Vitaly Churkin, Russia's deputy foreign minister and Moscow's special
envoy in former Yugoslavia, warned earlier that Nato's Partnership for Peace
agreements with former Warsaw Pact states in eastern Europe could be one
casualty of any air strike. 'The point here is not air strikes; it is
peace,' he said.
As the west seeks ways to capitalise on the ceasefire around Sarajevo and
move the peace process forward, Mr Douglas Hurd, British foreign secretary,
will today hold talks with Mr Alain Juppe, his French counterpart. Senior
officials from the European Union, the US, Russia and the UN are due to meet
tomorrow in Bonn.
Mr Christopher said that finding a settlement which met the reasonable
requirements of the Bosnian Moslems was a high priority, and that the
apparent success of Nato's new resolve over Sarajevo would boost peace
talks.
Removal of the Serb artillery eases but does not end the siege of Sarajevo
and its 380,000 inhabitants. Serb forces still control all access to the
city, although UN troops are monitoring the latest ceasefire, which has
restored some degree of normality.
Further reports, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
