<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 94 / Financial markets braced for further turbulence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON and GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International financial markets look set for another bout of turbulence
today after the sell-off that caused heavy falls in US and European bond and
equity markets late last Friday.
One senior marketmaker in UK equities said yesterday that the FT-SE 100, the
London market's leading stocks, could probably be marked down by as much as
60 points at the opening to try to head off any attempted selling by the big
institutions.
He said that 3,355 on the FT-SE 100 would be a benchmark for market
sentiment: 'If it closes above 3,355 we should stabilise.' The FT-SE 100
closed at 3,382.6 last Friday. Wall Street is closed today - Presidents'
Day.
Last week's sell-off came as bond dealers took fright at talk of
exceptionally heavy selling of international bonds by some big US hedge
funds, which are involved in aggressive short-term trading but seek to
offset exposure to changes in market rates. This was compounded by worries
about what Mr Alan Greenspan, US Federal Reserve chairman, will say to
Congress tomorrow in a review of monetary policy.
Asian centres will provide the first pointers to international market
performance today. In Tokyo, shares edged lower in thin morning trading,
with the Nikkei average down 18 at midday. Hong Kong stocks were sharply
down in early trade.
Mr Nick Knight, analyst at Nomura, the stockbroker, said: 'The Hong Kong
market is a critical and sensitive indicator of US money flows. If Hong Kong
is down 200 points we'll have a manageable fall in London but if it is
significantly larger than that, then it could be serious.'
Global investor, Page 22
Currency markets, Page 23
International bonds, Page 24
Equity markets, Page 25
